<!-- Surname spelled Sír by several English-language sources, including Sports-Reference and Tilastopaja. Most Hungarian sources support the spelling Sir, though, as do the '36 Olympic report and the ATFS and Athletics Weekly refs cited below -->
'''József Sir''' (born '''Schier'''; 28 April 1912 – 22 September 1996)<ref name="am">{{cite web |url=http://atletikamagazin.hu/content/view/56/47/ |title=Dr. Sir József (1912-1996) |author=Istenes, Vilmos |publisher=Atlétika Sport és Életmód Magazin |language=Hungarian |accessdate=27 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427231640/http://atletikamagazin.hu/content/view/56/47/ |archivedate=27 April 2014 |df= }}</ref> was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]]. He won three medals at the [[1934 European Athletics Championships|1934 European Championships]] and was a four-time [[International University Games]] gold medallist.

==Career==
Sir won three medals, two silvers and a bronze, at the inaugural [[European Athletics Championships|European Championships]] in [[Turin]] in 1934.<ref name="am"/><ref name="aw2">{{cite web |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/ec.htm |title=European Championships (Men) |publisher=''Athletics Weekly'' |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> He won silver in the [[200 metres]] behind [[Chris Berger]] of the Netherlands, with both clocking 21.5.<ref name="aw2"/> In the [[100 metres]] he ran 10.7 and placed third behind Berger (10.6) and Germany's [[Erich Borchmeyer]].<ref name="aw2"/> He won his third medal in the [[4 × 100 metres relay]] with the Hungarian team, which ran 41.4 and lost only to Germany.<ref name="am"/><ref name="aw2"/>

Sir won three gold medals at the [[1935 International University Games]] in [[Budapest]], running 10.8 and 21.6 for 100 and 200 metres and 41.6 with the Hungarian relay team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mefs.hu/!/nemzetkozi-sport/esemenyek/3-nemzetkozi-sport/351-6-nemzetkozi-egyetemi-jatekok-1935 |title=6. Nemzetközi Egyetemi Játékok - 1935 |publisher=Magyar Egyetemi-Főiskolai Sportszövetség |language=Hungarian |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="aw">{{cite web |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/wsg.htm |title=World Student Games (Pre-Universiade) |publisher=''[[Athletics Weekly]]'' |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> At the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] he advanced to the semi-finals in the [[Athletics at the 1936 Summer Olympics – Men's 100 metres|100 metres]]; he placed last in his semi-final and was eliminated.<ref name="sr">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/si/jozsef-sir-1.html |title=József Sír Bio, Stats and Results |publisher=Sports Reference LLC |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> In the [[Athletics at the 1936 Summer Olympics – Men's 200 metres|200 metres]] he went out in the quarterfinals, and the Hungarian relay team failed to qualify for the final.<ref name="sr"/>

Sir won four more medals at the International University Games in 1939. There were two competing meetings that year, in [[Monte Carlo]] and [[Vienna]];<ref name="aw"/> Sir participated in the [[1939 International University Games (UIE)|Vienna meet]], winning gold in the 100 metres (10.7), silver in the 200 metres (21.9) and bronze with the 4 × 100 metres relay team. He won another bronze in the 10 × 200 metres relay, a one-off event.<ref name="aw"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Nyári Egyetemi Világbajnokság - 1939 |url=http://www.mefs.hu/!/esemenynaptar/3-nemzetkozi-sport/355-nyari-egyetemi-vilagbajnoksag-1939 |publisher=Magyar Egyetemi-Főiskolai Sportszövetség |language=Hungarian |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>

Sir was Hungarian champion at both 100 and 200 metres in 1934, 1935 and 1939.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=arakatletika.hu |language=Hungarian |title=Férfi 100 Méteres Síkfutás |accessdate=27 April 2014 |url=http://www.arakatletika.hu/_user/browser/File/Eredmenyek/2007./1FERFI100MSIK.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=arakatletika.hu |language=Hungarian |title=Férfi 200 Méteres Síkfutás |accessdate=27 April 2014 |url=http://www.arakatletika.hu/_user/browser/File/Eredmenyek/2007./2FERFI200MSIK.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref> In addition, in 1934 he won the [[AAA Championships]] at [[100-yard dash|100 yards]] in 9.9.<ref name="am"/><ref name="aw3">{{cite web |url=http://www.gbrathletics.com/bc/bc2.htm |title=British Athletics Championships 1919-1939 |publisher=''Athletics Weekly'' |accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> His best time for 100 metres was 10.4, which he ran in [[Berlin]] on 1 July 1934;<ref name="atfs">{{cite web|url=http://atfs.org/historical/All-Time-List-At-Dec-1945.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=[[Association of Track and Field Statisticians]] |title=All-Time List As At 31 December 1945 |accessdate=27 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418234049/http://atfs.org/historical/All-Time-List-At-Dec-1945.pdf |archivedate=18 April 2014 |df= }}</ref> it was a [[Hungarian records in athletics|Hungarian record]], and remained so for more than thirty years.<ref name="am"/>

Sir served in the [[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]] Council from 1964 to 1984.<ref name="am"/> He proposed the IAAF Technical Aid Programme, which sought to develop the sport, and became its first director when it was approved.<ref name="am"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/download/download?filename=109b892a-9520-4d2f-a182-57cf4f78d404.pdf&urlslug=IAAF%20Constitution |format=PDF |publisher=International Association of Athletics Federations |accessdate=27 April 2014 |title=IAAF Constitution}}</ref>

